const jsonLd = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BlogPosting",
    "headline": "What to Do When You Have a Burst Pipe: Emergency Response Guide",
    "description": "Step-by-step guide for handling burst pipes. Immediate actions prevent extensive water damage.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Bristol Emergency Plumber"
    },
    "datePublished": "2024-01-20",
    "image": "https://bristolemergencyplumber.co.uk/assets/images/blog-burst-pipe.webp"
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="What to Do When You Have a Burst Pipe | Bristol Emergency Plumber"
  description="Emergency response guide for burst pipes. Immediate actions prevent water damage. Call Bristol Emergency Plumber 24/7."
  canonical="https://bristolemergencyplumber.co.uk/blog/what-to-do-burst-pipe/"
  ogTitle="What to Do When You Have a Burst Pipe"
  ogDescription="Step-by-step guide for handling burst pipes and preventing extensive water damage"
  currentPage="blog"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <div class="container">
      <ol>
        <li><a href="/">Home</a></li><li><a href="/blog/">Blog</a></li><li><span class="current">What to Do: Burst Pipe</span></li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <main id="main-content" role="main">
    <article>
      <section class="page-hero">
        <div class="container">
          <h1>What to Do When You Have a Burst Pipe: Emergency Response Guide</h1>
          <p class="article-meta">Published: January 2024 • Bristol Emergency Plumber</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <div class="container">
          <p>A burst pipe is a genuine emergency. Hundreds of litres of water flood your property within minutes, causing thousands in damage. Knowing what to do immediately after discovering a burst pipe—before the emergency plumber arrives—makes the critical difference between manageable damage and catastrophic loss.</p>

          <h2>First 60 Seconds: Stop the Water</h2>
          <p><strong>Your primary goal is stopping water flow immediately.</strong></p>

          <ol>
            <li><strong>Locate your mains stop tap.</strong> This is usually under the kitchen sink where the water supply enters your home. It may also be in the hallway, under the stairs, or in an external water meter box. Learn where this is now before emergencies strike.</li>
            <li><strong>Turn it clockwise firmly</strong> but don't force it. If it's stuck, apply gentle pressure and wait—it may unstick. Older taps sometimes resist after years without movement.</li>
            <li><strong>If you can't locate or operate the stop tap,</strong> call us immediately. Tell us about the burst pipe and that you cannot turn off water. We'll provide guidance and arrive urgently.</li>
            <li><strong>Turn off the boiler</strong> to prevent damage to heating systems from water exposure.</li>
            <li><strong>Check that water is flowing out of a tap,</strong> confirming the stopcock worked. If water still flows, the stopcock has failed and you need emergency help even more urgently.</li>
          </ol>

          <h2>Immediately After (First 5-10 Minutes)</h2>

          <h3>Protect Your Property</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Move electrical items, furniture, and valuables away from water</li>
            <li>Close doors to contain water to affected areas</li>
            <li>Place towels under visible water to soak it up</li>
            <li>Open windows for ventilation</li>
            <li>If there's visible water pooling, use a wet/dry vacuum if you have one</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Call Bristol Emergency Plumber</h3>
          <p>Phone us immediately: <a href="tel:+441174280200"><strong>0117 428 0200</strong></a></p>
          <p>Have this information ready:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Your location/postcode</li>
            <li>Description of where the burst is (under sink, in bathroom, in walls, etc.)</li>
            <li>Whether you've turned off water successfully</li>
            <li>Your phone number for our plumber to call when arriving</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Document the Damage</h3>
          <p>For insurance purposes, photograph affected areas and items. Your insurer may need evidence of damage. But prioritise safety and water containment over documentation.</p>

          <h2>While Waiting for the Plumber</h2>

          <h3>Continue Damage Mitigation</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Keep collecting water in buckets or towels</li>
            <li>Continue moving valuable items away from water</li>
            <li>Open more doors and windows for maximum drying</li>
            <li>If water is entering electrified areas, avoid contact and don't use electrical items there</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Locate the Burst If Possible</h3>
          <p>If you can safely identify where the burst is (visible from outside, in an accessible pipe), note its location. This helps our plumber quickly identify and repair the problem. Don't excavate or attempt temporary repairs.</p>

          <h3>Don't Use Your Mains Water</h3>
          <p>With the stopcock off, you can't use taps normally. Your mains water isn't available. Don't attempt to turn the stopcock back on to use water briefly—this defeats water damage mitigation and risks damaging your flooring worse during our diagnostic.</p>

          <h2>Common Burst Locations</h2>
          <p>Common places where bursts occur:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Under kitchen sinks where pipes are exposed to cold</li>
            <li>Pipes running through unheated lofts (freeze in winter)</li>
            <li>Pipes along external walls (cold exposure)</li>
            <li>Older copper pipes with internal corrosion damage (pinhole leaks become bursts)</li>
            <li>Buried external pipes damaged by ground movement or tree roots</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>After the Plumber Completes Repairs</h2>

          <h3>Reopening Your Water Supply</h3>
          <p>Once repairs are complete, our plumber will turn the stopcock back on gradually, checking for leaks. Don't rush this—slow reopening identifies remaining problems.</p>

          <h3>Drying Your Property</h3>
          <p>After turning water back on, continue drying. Leave windows open, run dehumidifiers, and remove wet carpets and furnishings to prevent mold. Professional drying services are worthwhile for extensive damage.</p>

          <h3>Insurance Claims</h3>
          <p>Contact your home insurance immediately. You'll need photos, a plumber's report (we can provide one), and lists of damaged items. Your insurer will guide next steps for claims processing.</p>

          <h2>Prevention: Avoid Future Bursts</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Insulate pipes in lofts and under floors with pipe lagging</li>
            <li>Ensure good ventilation in unheated spaces (prevents freezing)</li>
            <li>Consider trace heating for particularly exposed pipes</li>
            <li>For older properties with failing pipes, plan replacement before failure</li>
            <li>Know where your stopcock is and how to operate it</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Emergency Contact Information</h2>
          <p>Store this phone number where everyone in your household can find it:</p>
          <p style="font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;"><a href="tel:+441174280200">Bristol Emergency Plumber: 0117 428 0200</a></p>
          <p>Available 24/7 • Average response: 30-60 minutes</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="cta-section">
        <div class="container">
          <h2>Burst Pipe Emergency?</h2>
          <p>Don't wait. Call us now for immediate assistance.</p>
          <div class="cta-buttons">
            <a href="tel:+441174280200" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Call Now: 0117 428 0200</a>
          </div>
          <p class="cta-note">Available 24/7 • Average response time: 30-60 minutes</p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
